CREscendo Tutorial: Analysis of 10X Genomics human PBMC Single-Cell Multiome Data

Introduction

scATAC-seq captures fragments through Tn5 tagmentation, which allows for precise analysis of regulatory elements by examining the Tn5 cleavage sites. Unfortunately, the detailed base-resolution information is often condensed and simplified in current peak-based scATAC-seq analyses. The peak calling software, such as Cellranger, generates a broad range of peak sizes, while MACS2 can identify significantly smaller peaks. However, even these smaller peaks generally exceed the size of a single cis-regulatory element (CRE) as annotated by ENCODE. To address this issue, we introduce the CREscendo framework, which is designed to analyze differential usage of CREs by examining differences in Tn5 cleavage frequencies across cell types. This approach helps to recover regulatory signals that peak-based analyses often overlook.

Specifically, CREscendo segments each peak into designated regions such as CRE1, CRE2, and so forth, along with non-CRE areas. For each peak, a frequency vector is constructed, and a chi-square test is conducted to detect statistically significant differences in cleavage frequencies across different cell types. The resulting p-values are adjusted for multiple testing, and the significant CREs are identified. The CREscendo framework is implemented as an R package, available on GitHub.

Installation

To install the CREscendo package, you can use the code.

devtools::install_github("ChenMengjie/CREscendo")

Then load the following libraries used in this tutorial:

library(Signac)
library(Seurat)
library(EnsDb.Hsapiens.v75)
library(TxDb.Hsapiens.UCSC.hg38.knownGene)
library(CREscendo)
library(ggrepel)
library(tictoc)

Dataset: PBMC multiome from a Healthy Donor - Granulocytes Removed Through Cell Sorting (10k)

We downloaded the PBMC multiome dataset, which includes peak files and fragment files, from 10x Genomics. The multiome platform produces data that includes both ATAC and RNA profiles from the same cells. Each cell’s data is linked by a unique cell barcode. The dataset is estimated to contain 11,898 cells. We conducted quality control using Signac as showed in their tutorial and the object is saved as pbmc_10X_multiome.rds, downloadable from this link.

pbmc <- readRDS("/path/to/pbmc_10X_multiome.rds")
pbmc
peaks.gr <- granges(pbmc@assays$peaks)
peaks.gr <- peaks.gr[grep("chr", seqnames(peaks.gr))]
peaks.gr

For the annotation of cis-regulatory elements (CREs), we utilized resources from the ENCODE Encyclopedia, specifically the Registry of cCREs Version 3 from SCREEN. This resource details 1,063,878 candidate CREs identified by segregating signals across all biospecimen sourced from 1,518 cell types. These CREs are categorized further into candidate promoters, candidate proximal enhancers, candidate distal enhancers, and are also annotated based on their CTCF binding status.

We have implemented functions to load the CREs from the ENCODE SCREEN V3 directly.

CRE_gr <- CREscendo:::load_CRE_annotations(genome = "hg38")

Creating a CREscendo Test Data Object

In the CREscendo test, Tn5 cleavage frequencies are used as the input. However, this information is not readily available in the peak file alone. To obtain Tn5 cleavage data, we need to screen the fragment files. Given that these fragment files are typically quite large, we opt for the Tabix-indexed file format. Tabix files are compressed and indexed, allowing for efficient data retrieval.

The PrepareCREscendoObject function serves as our tool for constructing a CREscendo object. This involves several steps:

  1. Processing and annotating Genomic Peaks: Initially, we process genomic peaks, which are typically stored in a GenomicRanges object (peaks_gr).

  2. Associating Peaks with CREs: We associate these peaks with cis-regulatory elements (CREs), thereby establishing their regulatory context.

  3. Compiling Cleavage Site Counts: The core aspect of the process involves compiling counts of cleavage sites. This requires accessing the Tabix-indexed file (tabix_file) containing relevant fragment data.

The PrepareCREscendoObject function expects the following inputs:

  • peaks_gr: GenomicRanges object containing genomic peak locations.
  • tabix_file: Path to a Tabix-indexed file containing fragments relevant to the peaks.
  • cell_annotation: Data frame containing cell annotations with columns for cell name and cell type.
  • celltype_list (Optional): A vector of cell types to include in the analysis. If NULL, all unique cell types from cell_annotation will be used.
  • CRE_gr: GenomicRanges object for cis-regulatory elements.
  • tssRegion: Numeric vector of length 2 specifying the region around transcription start sites to consider for annotation (defaults to c(-1000, 1000)).
  • TxDb: A TxDb object containing transcript annotations.
  • annoDb: Character string, the Bioconductor annotation package for organism-specific data. Default is “org.Hs.eg.db” for human.
  • multiCREs: Logical value indicating whether to include peaks with multiple CREs (TRUE) or all peaks (FALSE). Default is TRUE.

This function streamlines the process, allowing for efficient preparation and construction of the necessary data object for the CREscendo test.

We applied PrepareCREscendoObject to extract Tn5 cleavage sites for selected cell types in PBMC Multiome dataset. Cell annotations should be provided as a two-column data frame. The first column should contain the cell IDs, and the second column should contain the corresponding cell types The cell annotation for this example data set has been saved in an RData file.

load("/path/to/cell_annotation_PBMC_multiome.RData")
head(cell_annotation)

Tn5 cleavage sites are identified by using the start and end sites of each segment from fragment files. We annotate each peak using ENCODE-defined CREs. For peaks with k overlapping CREs, we divide the peak into k+1 segments (cre1, cre2, …, crek) plus an additional segment for base pairs within the peak not covered by any CREs. For each cell type, we construct a frequency vector that represents the number of cleavage sites falling within each segment. The final CREscendo object contains annotated peaks, CRE associations, and cleavage event counts for further analysis.

Testing CRE Association with specified cell types within a CREscendo Object

The main function CREtest() performs chi-squared tests on CREs associated with peaks within a CREscendo object. It evaluates differential CRE activities between two groups of cells.

The required input includes: - x: A CREscendo object containing the necessary datasets for CRE analysis. - celltypes: One or two cell types. Must be cell types included in the CREscendo object. If one cell type is specified, the comparison will be made between the specified cell type and all other cell types. If two cell types are specified, the comparison will be made between the two specified cell types.

For each peak, we perform a chi-square test with degrees of freedom equal to k (k is the number of overlapping CREs). In the chi-square tests for comparison, with two cell types A and B, we conduct the test first using A as the reference population, and then repeat using B. The final p-value is determined as the maximum (less significant) from these two tests. After generating test statistics for all peaks, we apply false discovery rate (FDR) adjustments to correct for multiple comparisons. We further quantified the contribution of CRE by breaking down the overall chi-square statistic into partial chi-square statistic from each CRE.

As an exmaple, we performed the CREscendo test between CD14 Mono and CD8 Naive cells in PBMC multiome dataset.

tic()
comparison1 <- CREtest(pbmc_CREscendo, celltypes = c("CD14 Mono", "CD8 Naive"))
toc()

To refine our results from the chi-squared test, we can utilize the Filter() function. This function is designed to extract and return high-confidence results from the summary component of the chi-squared test, enabling prioritized downstream analysis. The Filter() function accepts the following parameters: - x: A CREscendoTested object containing the results from CRE association tests. - fdr_cutoff: A numeric value specifying the false discovery rate (FDR) adjusted p-value threshold for filtering the results. The default is 0.05. - coverage_cutoff: A numeric value specifying the cutoff of the number of fragments across all cells within the same type for each peak region for filtering the results. The default is 100. - abs_diff_cutoff: A numeric value specifying the cutoff of the absolute difference in the CRE frequencies between two cell types. The default is 0.2. By applying these filtering criteria, we can focus our analysis on the most significant relevant CRE associations.

comparison1_summary <- Filter(comparison1)

We can further filter out non-coding genes.

coding_genes <- grep(pattern = "^(?!.*(?:MIR|LINC|AS|LOC|HSA|SNHG|TCONS|XLOC|RP[0-9]+|NR_[0-9]+)).*$", x = comparison1_summary$SYMBOL, value = TRUE, perl = TRUE)
coding_comparison1_summary <- comparison1_summary[comparison1_summary$SYMBOL%in%coding_genes, ]

Visualization of CREscendo Test Results

The function Visualize() is designed to visualize cleavage sites of different cell types for a specific peak or peaks from a specific gene within a CREscendoTested object. This function facilitates the extraction and visualization of relevant data, including cleavage sites, CRE annotations, and CRE frequencies within tested cell types.

The following is a visualization of the CREscendo test results for a specific peak (chr3-101848856-101851038).

Visualize(comparison1, which_peak = "chr3-101848856-101851038")

If you are interested in a specific peak, like the contribution of each CRE to the chi-square statistics, you can extract more details using the Extract() function.

info_for_a_peak <- Extract(comparison1, which_peak = "chr3-101848856-101851038")
info_for_a_peak$plot_contribution

Comparing with differential accessbility analysis

For the PBMC_multiome dataset, we performed differential accessibility (DA) tests between different cell types using logistic regression. To account for variations in sequencing depth, we included the total number of peaks as a covariate, following the recommendations in Signac. This step is computationally intensive.

DefaultAssay(pbmc) <- 'peaks'
tic()
da_peaks <- FindMarkers(
  object = pbmc,
  ident.1 = "CD14 Mono",
  ident.2 = "CD8 Naive",
  test.use = 'LR',
  latent.vars = 'nCount_peaks'
)
head(da_peaks)

We further compared the results from CREscendo and DA tests.

chisq_test_summary <- Summarize(comparison1)
commons <- intersect(rownames(chisq_test_summary), rownames(da_peaks))
all_stats <- cbind(chisq_test_summary[commons, ], da_peaks[commons, ])


# Updated ggplot2 code with ggrepel for non-overlapping text labels
dq <- ggplot(all_stats, aes(x = avg_log2FC, y = chisq_stat)) +
  geom_point( size = 0.8) +
  geom_text_repel(data = subset(all_stats, chisq_stat > 2500),
                  aes(label = SYMBOL),
                  max.overlaps = Inf,
                  box.padding = 0.5,
                  point.padding = 0.5,
                  size = 3,  color = 'darkred') +
  xlim(-6, 6) +  # Slightly wider x-axis limits
  ylim(min(all_stats$chisq_stat), max(all_stats$chisq_stat) + 500) +  # Extend y-axis if necessary
  theme_classic() + labs(title = "CD14 Mono vs. CD8 Naive", x = "Avg log2FC", y = "Chi-square statistics") +
  theme(plot.margin = margin(1, 1, 1, 1, "cm"))  # Set x-axis limits 
dq
